The failure is about LLM output quality/judgment, not about HTTP transport behavior.","test_description":"Craft 3–5 nuanced query examples (e.g., a query whose literal keywords match item A best but whose evident intent aligns with item B). Feed the raw similarity-ranked top-K results and the query to the real LLM re-ranker. Assert that the output ordering differs from the input ordering for at least one result position in the majority of runs.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.02,"Integration":0.04,"System":0.06,"Agentic":0.74,"Workflow":0.14}},{"behavior_id":4,"description":"A query with no close matches in the database returns an empty result set rather than low-relevance noise.","minimum_level":"Integration","justification":"MOCK-MISS: The failure is in the threshold/filtering logic between the vector DB result layer and the response layer—specifically, whether a similarity score below the configured cutoff correctly suppresses results. This is a module-boundary bug (DB returns low-score hits; application must filter them out), not a single-function bug. REAL-INFRA: A local vector store seeded with test data and an injected query vector orthogonal to all stored vectors fully reproduces the failure. No real HTTP or OS primitives needed. LLM-DEP: Filtering against a cosine-similarity threshold is deterministic; the embedding can be a pre-computed stub vector. INTEGRATION-BRAKE: (a) No real OS/network required. (b) No AI/ML quality dependency—threshold logic is deterministic. (c) No multi-step chain. Stays at Integration.","test_description":"Seed a local vector store with N product embeddings. Inject a query vector that is provably orthogonal (or maximally distant) to all stored vectors—bypassing the real embedding model. Issue the search and assert the returned result set is empty, confirming the similarity threshold filter is applied rather than returning the lowest-scoring candidates.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.06,"Integration":0.52,"System":0.28,"Agentic":0.1,"Workflow":0.04}},{"behavior_id":5,"description":"The end-to-end latency from receiving the query to returning re-ranked results stays below 2 seconds for the median case.","minimum_level":"Workflow","justification":"REAL-INFRA: Latency is physically meaningless with mocks—stubs return in microseconds regardless of what real network RTT, embedding inference time, vector DB query time, and LLM re-ranking inference time actually cost. The 2-second budget must be measured across all live legs. LLM-DEP: Re-ranking uses a real LLM whose inference time varies across calls; stubs hide this variance. MULTI-STEP: The pipeline chains at minimum two AI/ML model calls in sequence—embedding model call (step 1) → vector DB query → LLM re-ranker call (step 2)—making this a multi-agentic-step pipeline. All three KEY-QUESTION flags (REAL-INFRA, LLM-DEP, MULTI-STEP) fire, requiring Workflow. REJECTION-GATE: Why not System? System covers real HTTP but not the LLM inference non-determinism and the chained agentic steps that dominate latency variance here.","test_description":"Issue N≥100 representative search queries against the full live pipeline (real embedding service → real vector DB → real LLM re-ranker). Record wall-clock latency per request from HTTP request receipt to response returned. Assert that the median (p50) latency is below 2000 ms. Log p95 for observability. Run in an environment that matches production network topology.","plan_consistent":true,"plan_consistent_note":null,"level_probabilities":{"Unit":0.01,"Integration":0.03,"System":0.16,"Agentic":0.2,"Workflow":0.6}}]},"caller":{"type":"direct"}}],"stop_reason":null,"stop_sequence":null,"usage":{"input_tokens":3,"cache_creation_input_tokens":10026,"cache_read_input_tokens":3199,"cache_creation":{"ephemeral_5m_input_tokens":0,"ephemeral_1h_input_tokens":10026},"output_tokens":8,"service_tier":"standard","inferenc